===Etymology===
First attested around 1350. From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{term|abominacioun|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|frm|en}} {{term|abomination||horror, disgust|lang=frm}}, from {{etyl|LL.|en}} {{m|la|abōminātiō||abomination}}; {{term|ab||away from|lang=la}} + {{m|la|ōminārī||prophesy, foreboding}}, from {{m|la|ōmin||omen}}.<ref>{{R:CDOE|page=4}}</ref>

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|RP|US}} {{IPA|/əˌbɑm.əˈneɪ.ʃn̩/|/əˌbɑm.ɪˈneɪ.ʃn̩/|lang=en}}
* {{rhymes|eɪʃən|lang=en}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# An [[abominable]] act; a [[disgusting]] [[vice]]; a [[despicable]] [[habit]]. {{defdate|First attested around 1150 to 1350.}}<ref name=SOED>{{R:SOED5|page=6}}</ref>
# The feeling of extreme [[disgust]] and hatred; [[abhorrence]]; [[detestation]]; [[loathing]]. {{defdate|First attested around 1350 to 1470.}}<ref name=SOED/>
# {{context|obsolete|lang=en}} A state that excites detestation or abhorrence; pollution. {{defdate|Attested from around (1350 - 1470) to the late 15<sup>th</sup> century.}}<ref name=SOED/>
# That which is [[abominable]], [[shameful]]ly vile; an object that excites disgust and hatred; very often with religious undertones. {{defdate|First attested around 1350 to 1470.}}<ref name=SOED/>
#* Antony, most large in his '''abominations'''. Shakespeare, ''Antony and Cleopatra, III-vi''

